        "id": 1016434
      },
      "writtenOn": "2016-02-11T18:43:14Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "The problem I was unsatisfied with was what to do if -V specifies a path not of the form \"/proc/PID/ns/mnt\".  E.g., if I symlink or bind mount /proc/PID/ns/mnt to /tmp/mntns and use -V /tmp/mntns, what should happen?  Do we expect minijail0 to still work then, or is it okay to require users to specify -V of the form \"/proc/PID/ns/mnt\"?  (And if so, should/can we change it to just \"-V PID\"?)\n\n\nAlternative solution: can we defer the ELF linkage check until after we\u0027ve applied the mount namespace / chroot / bind mount changes?  That would let us also check that PRELOADPATH is actually available in the target namespace too.  (It looks like glibc ld.so just ignores LD_PRELOAD entries that aren\u0027t available.)",
      "parentUuid": "7df0ecdc_64ee5218",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 14,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 16,
        "endChar": 22
      },
      "revId": "80d15313f9f676533bac488dea5a5ed765ae246f",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "fde3fc1c_9b22b73a",
        "filename": "/COMMIT_MSG",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 16,
